At least the Lisp guys have figured out how to write parsers and lexers by now.  (They even grok lexical scoping.)<p>I guess we can't blame PHP for preserving the $ in front of variable-names with all the legacy code lying around.  But the following should parse in a sane language:<p><pre><code>  $width = getimagesize($filename)[0];
</code></pre>
Adding support for this would not break legacy code.  Nobody can tell me that naming all intermediate results like<p><pre><code>  $sizes = getimagesize($img);
  $width = $sizes[0];
</code></pre>
is such a preferable style, that the parser should enforce it.<p>By the way, this is how PHP pretends to support higher order functions:<p><pre><code>  function cube($n) {return($n * $n * $n);}
  $a = array(1, 2, 3, 4, 5);
  $b = array_map("cube", $a);</code></pre>
